## Purpose

The “Purpose” is to outline the domain knowledge, technical requirements and behavioral qualities a small language model needs to function as a newsroom copy editor, specifically one that checks for AP Style adherence, fact-checking accuracy and transcript/quote fidelity.

### In Scope

- AP Style Guidebook rules, such as abbreviations, numerals, titles and oxford commas (I know, it looks gross!)
- Understanding the technical mechanisms that enable an SLM to specialize in a narrow task (LoRA, QLoRA, supervised fine-tuning)
- Defining what “correct” editorial behavior looks like so it can be translated into training examples and evaluation rubrics
- Researching evaluation methods that measure whether the model *behaves* like a copy editor, not just whether it produces fluent text
- Building structured knowledge that can be passed directly to AI as context during development and fine-tuning conversations

### Out of Scope

- General LLM capabilities not relevant to editorial tasks (e.g. code generation, math reasoning)
- Deployment infrastructure, API design or production engineering concerns
- Replacing editorial judgment wholesale. The SLM is a checking and flagging tool, not an autonomous editor

