## DOK 3: Insights

- **Insight 1:** **The job of an editor is solely to surface and flag problems, which is the same constraint a reliable AI editor must internalize.** Cutting words and rearranging syntax in the name of efficiency and clarity may alter the reporter’s tone or change the meaning of the sentence entirely. While a human has the discernment to judge how to preserve a writer’s voice, an LLM or SLM must require rigorous training fine-tuning to develop the same skill. Thus, we cannot trust an AI model purely on its context of shifting an entire article to a “journalistic” tone, as it does not have enough discretion for stylistic decisions.
- **Insight 2:** **The same deterministic property that makes copy editing automatable is also what makes it the ideal training signal for fine-tuning.** AP Style rules, fact-checking verdicts, and hyperlink checks all produce clean binary labels (correct/incorrect, supported/unsupported, resolves/broken). Training data for a copy-editing SLM can be constructed with high confidence without expensive human preference labeling as the foundation already exists in the AP Stylebook and IFCN methodology. Most fine-tuning projects fail because the desired behavior is too subjective to label consistently. A journalism SLM sidesteps this problem entirely.
- **Insight 3: Dataset quality matters more than model size for narrow editorial tasks.** A 7B parameter model fine-tuned on 500 high-quality AP Style correction examples will outperform a 70B base model prompted to follow AP Style because fine-tuning encodes the behavior into weights while prompting only activates existing patterns. The bottleneck for this project is curation of clean, well-labeled editorial training examples.

